description.narrative:
AI4D Africa

This first year of programming has laid the foundations of the AI4D Africa initiative. All the planned calls have been launched and all major projects (except for the four innovation research networks and the Data Science Africa innovation project) approved.

The program has been adaptive and opportunistic. Strategic programmatic adjustments have been made during the year, such as reallocating funds towards an additional policy research centre in East Africa, in addition to the centres in West and South Africa, based on the complementary. Moreover, projects, not in the original proposal, have been initiated, such as the Professional Development Award program and the Villgro small grants project. AI4D Africa has also been active in seeking out ways to leverage additional funds and increase regional and global collaboration. Some examples of resulting collaborations include:

- Climate Action: Discussions are on going with the Inter-American Development Bank about the possibility of replicating the African network in Latin America. Moreover, a collaboration with Climate Change AI (CCAI), who have raised USD 3m for a global network on ML and Climate Change, has been established. The plan is to connect the AI4D Africa network on Climate Action with the CCAI network;

- Health: IDRCs Global Health Division is in the process of finalizing funding for an AI4D innovation research network on sexual and reproductive health (~CAD 1.2m). This hub will be included in the network of AI4D innovation hubs, allowing for cross-project learning and knowledge sharing;

- Responsible AI Index: Following the creation of the AI Government Readiness Index and its sub-index on Responsible AI, interest has been received to fund a full, global, primary data, responsible AI index. IDRC will fund a 1-year project with the HSRC to develop the methodology which will integrate into their role as the African Observatory on Responsible AI. A larger externally funded project with the government of Canada will be pursued to pay for a few years of the index. This may also include the gender and inclusion work supported by IDRC;

- LACUNA Fund: IDRC is a founding funder of the LACUNA Fund, the worlds first fund dedicated to the creation of labeled data sets needed to solve urgent challenges in low- and middle-income contexts globally. The first three LACUNA Fund calls have targeted sub-Saharan Africa in the areas of languages, agriculture, and health. It is anticipate that some researchers in the AI4D Africa innovation research networks will be able to put these data sets into use. Note that the LACUNA Fund plans on launching more calls on languages, agriculture, climate change mitigation and climate change and health.

Over the year, the brand and visibility of the initiative has grown rapidly, with more than 1,500 followers on Twitter and over 1,000 subscribers to the bi-weekly newsletter. The website for the initiative has also been launched which enables to promote the latest funding opportunities, research publications, partner organizations, blogs, and more.

In the narrative report for 2020-06-17 to 2021-03-31 IDRC has made an environmental assessment which allows Sida to add two policy markers to the AI4D component of the contribution ("aid to environment" and "climate change - mitigation"). From the report it is clear that the AI4D program does have several activities in place to bring about positive environmental change as well as to help minimise any negative environmental impact from the program. This includes:

- The Climate Action Innovation Research Network: The goal of the Climate Action network is to advance the responsible development and deployment of home-grown AI innovations to tackle pressing challenges emerging from climate change in Africa. This activity will also be collaborating with a larger initiative that will support similar research on machine learning and climate change around the globe;

- Reporting: A question has been included in the template for technical reporting by lead organizations on the environmental sustainability of their activities. This question will be used as a prompt for an increased focus on environmental impacts of the program going forward;

- CO2 Emission:The training of some machine learning models can be quite energy intensive, generating a concern about the CO2 footprint of artificial intelligence. Therefore, all machine learning innovations supported through the innovation networks will be required to provide an accounting of the estimated energy and CO2 emissions of their model training.

AI4COVID

The call for proposals was launched in June 2020 and selection concluded in August 2020 via an external expert committee. IDRC and Sida split the funding of proposals, with our (Sidas) funding directed primarily at African recipients. In October 2020, we (Sida) decided to support two additional projects which were selected via the shortlist. As of May 2021, all nine AI4COVID projects have been allocated and have officially started program activities.

As of August 2021, most projects are in the early stages of data collection, analysis and model building or deployment, though some have progressed and are already now actively informing policy and decision making.

Other key activities and results during the first year include:

- An inception meeting was held with the program partners in December 2020;

- Canadas Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister of Foreign Affairs supported the launch of one of the AI4COVID Response projects with York University;

- A first quarterly learning event took place in the first half of 2021. The objectives of the event were to advance learning and practice on (i) how to design gender responsive data projects; and (ii) making data actionable through policy influence and impact pathways.
